  "prompt": "If black holes pull in all matter due to a high gravitational pull, but light has no mass and also isn't considered matter, how can black holes exist?",
  "response": "Black holes can exist because they warp spacetime itself, not just pull in matter. According to Einstein's theory of General Relativity, gravity is the result of the curvature of spacetime caused by mass and energy. A black hole is an extremely dense object where this curvature becomes so extreme that it forms a region from which nothing, not even light, can escape.\n\nLight follows the curvature of spacetime. When it passes near a massive object, such as a black hole, its path is bent due to the warped spacetime. At the event horizon of a black hole, this curvature becomes so intense that all paths lead inward, trapping light along with any other particles or objects.\n\nThus, even though light has no mass, it is still affected by the gravitational field of a black hole because that field is a manifestation of the warped spacetime. This is why black holes can exist and why they can pull in light, making them appear \"black\" since no light can escape to be seen.",
